result.execSummary:
The defendant Timothy E. Rasmuson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Penalty - Contact after Domestic Abuse Arrest]. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: $250 fine plus costs. (fine and costs have been paid in full)

Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement

Defendant Timothy E. Rasmuson in court with attorney Brett E Reetz.  Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Minute sheet. State gives plea agreement.  Court questions defendant on change of plea.  Rights/elements/max. penalties reviewed with defendant.  Defendant enters no contest plea to Ct. 2. Defense stipulates to factual basis to accept plea.  Court finds plea made freely, knowingly and voluntarily but withholds accepting of the plea to allow defendant the opportunity to complete terms of the Deferred Acceptance of Guilty Plea Agreement. Court dismisses Ct. 1 but reads in for sentencing. Court reviews DAGPA with defendant, approves and signs agreement. Upon successful completion of DAGPA, State will, after 12 months, move to amend charge to a County Ordinance of Disorderly Conduct and matter can be disposed by written stipulation. Bond remains in effect.  Deferred prosecution agreement hearing scheduled for December 5, 2016 at 11:45 am.
